3. Scenario 1: USB Drive Wipe Recovery (Manual Carving)

3.1 Observations
	•	Disk image: Challenge1_Manual_Carve_usb.img
	•	MBR present but partition table empty
→ Indicates formatted drive
	•	Residual data still present → recoverable

⸻

3.2 Manual Carving Process

Step 1: Identify Signatures
	•	Example:
	•	PNG Header → 89504E47
	•	PNG Footer → 49454E44AE426082

Step 2: Locate Offsets
	•	Header offset → 0001069056
	•	Footer offset → 0001526433

⸻

Step 3: Extract File
Method 1: Hex Editor
	•	Select byte range (start → end)
	•	Save as .png

Method 2: dd (preferred)

dd if=Challenge1_Manual_Carve_usb.img of=Image.png bs=1 skip=<start> count=<size>

Example:

dd if=Challenge1_Manual_Carve_usb.img of=Image.png bs=1 skip=134483968 count=463


⸻

Step 4: Verify File
Using:

exiftool Image.png

Findings:
	•	Valid PNG file
	•	Metadata includes:
	•	Resolution
	•	Compression
	•	File timestamps

⸻

3.3 Key Insight
	•	Formatting ≠ deletion of data
	•	Data persists until overwritten

⸻

4. Scenario 2: Slack Space Recovery

4.1 Concept: Slack Space
	•	Unused bytes inside allocated clusters
	•	Contains residual data from previous files

⸻

4.2 Tool Used: binwalk

binwalk Challenge2_slack_space.img


⸻

4.3 Findings
	•	MPEG transport stream at offset:
	•	268782594
	•	Other artifacts:
	•	MySQL index files
	•	EXT filesystem fragments

⸻

4.4 Analysis Process
	1.	Navigate to offset in hex editor
	2.	Identify signature (e.g., 0x47 for MPEG TS)
	3.	Confirm file structure
	4.	Extract using:

binwalk -e Challenge2_slack_space.img


⸻

4.5 Output
	•	Extracted directory:

_Challenge2_slack_space.img.extracted/



⸻

4.6 Key Insight
	•	Slack space is valuable for hidden residual evidence
	•	Fragmentation complicates manual recovery

